deck_excerpt: It's almost entirely playsets of cards that are banned/restricted on Master Duel.
deck_description: It's almost entirely playsets of cards that are banned/restricted on Master Duel.

As of now, there's 3 DMC lists in the works right now. They are Dogmatika Charmer Magistus, Diabellestar Charmer Magistus, and Diabellestar Centurion Magistus.

Here's a different way to play Centurion if interested in not just Calamity Turbo (or if it gets banned).

Any Centurion starter card allows you to make Zoroa on your opp turn, to lock them out after you know what they are playing. If you open Emblema, Diabellestar, Zoroa, you can end on I:P, Possessed Partnerships, Zoroa Lock, and the board wipe Sinful Spoil.

In my testing, This deck loses to Nibiru if you try to extend super hard, so if anyone can map out lines that play around Nibiru it would be appreciated. Shame that Primera has a once per turn SS restriction as well.

Hope you enjoy the list!

test

Greetings! In this deck, we will burn our opponent to death with Scarlight. For context, we will try to fill the board as many Effect Monsters as possible and detonate them all with Scarlight. "Shien's Spy" can pass some to opposing side to not feel overloaded while you will take as many turns as you can with Arcana.

 

 

Gameplan

1) Place "ME-PSY-YA" on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon" to where Saryuja points to. From here on, pick up spells needed with "Primal Seed". As long as you target "Primal Seed" each other, it won't be a huge deal.

2) Place "Light Barrier" and Special Summon "Arcana", either via "Saryuja" or "Monster Reborn". Pick the outcome to heads to take as many turns as you like.

3) Then, place "Cynet Universe" to make sure the attack values of Chaos and Saryuja are higher than Scarlight to not detonate both by accident.

4) Revive Effect Monsters with "Monster Reborn" and pass to your opponent with "Shien's Spy". When everything is full, trigger Scarlight to unload a huge damage.

5) End your turn and deliver two of your monsters to GY and take an extra turn. No matter what, you shouldn't send Arcana+Chaos+Saryuja+Scarlight to GY.

6) Repeat what was explained into #4 and #5 until your opponent is dead. Also, shuffle back a Normal Monster into your deck with "Cynet Universe" to not deck out.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have played the tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Pot of Acquisitiveness" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 60 SR and 60 UR!

- "Arcana Force" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Dugares" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Scarlight" can be found within "Savage Crimson Dragon" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 600 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: FTK, no Bishbaalkin, no other Main Deck cards needed, doesn't lose to ash.
deck_description:
To start the Main Combo, get either two Telefons or Telefons+Platinum Gadget on field.

Two Telefons: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52614349

Telefons + Platinum Gadget: https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52617894

 

If your opponent is occupying a zone (requires three Telefons):

(Left occupied): https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52707429

(Right occupied): https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=721052-52707915

 

Tips:

Your goal every game is to get 2+ Telefons into rotation and OTK your opponent.

Therion "King" Regulus acts as both negation and an extender to get out Platinum Gadget.

Small world bridges usually end with Gizmek Naganaki (Light). Use its first effect to get Telefon, second effect to get whatever your small world bridge was (typically another Telefon or Gizmek Orochi (Dark)).

Cyberse Clock Dragon is not a hard once per turn. The second summon needs to be chain blocked by Clock Lizard's effect to avoid ash blossom. Pay attention to remaining cards in deck when fusion summoning using material from grave; you have to mill the exact amount.

 

Extra Deck is extremely tight now that Bishbaalkin is banned. There may be other options if you allow yourself some main deck bricks. Machu Mech is a fun and interactive card for both players.

Category: Tournament Meta Deck OCG

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: 维尼写

Tournament: Superbrand Top Deck   - August 26th 2023

Placement: Champion

This deck is a pile of some very powerful engines put together so that you can end up summoning enough threats to win.

It uses a "Superheavy Samurai" engine to get plays going. If you draw into a bike you can use its effect to search for wakaushi and start some synchro plays. If this doesn't work the deck also runs an "Adventure Token" engine to be able to get out an omni-negate. There is also a "Tearlaments" package along with the Ishizu cards to be able to summon out monsters such as "Predaplant Dracostapelia" and "Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart". Finally there is a small "Kashtira" package to be able to get out some powerful cards to disrupt opponents plays.

deck_excerpt: Cyber Summon Blaster Burn ft. Arcana+Primal Seed
deck_description:
Hello and welcome to another guide, where I'll be explaining how to burn your opponent down with "Cyber Summon Blaster" thanks to taking extra turns with Arcana and reviving back and forth a Machine monster. Let me explain.

 

Gameplan

1) Place ME-PSY-YA on Pendulum Zone and Special Summon "Chaos Emperor Dragon". From here on, use "Primal Seed" cards to cycle combo pieces. As long as you target "Primal Seed" cards with each other, it won't be a problem.

2) Place "Light Barrier" and Special Summon Arcana, either via Saryuja or with "Monster Reborn", if discarded by Dugares/Ravenous. Choose the outcome of heads to skip your opponent's turn at the cost of two of your monsters being delivered to GY. Don't send Arcana and Chaos by accident and make sure you have two monsters available, which can be arranged with "Monster Reborn".

3) Set all of "Cyber Summon Blaster" and one of "Primal Seed" cards. End your turn but not before changing "Activation Confirmation" to "Switch+Hold" and setting to "ON" in-game to not miss any action, which can be edited in "Duel" section of settings page.

4) It's your turn now. Activate all of "Cyber Summon Blaster" trap cards.

5) Now, here is infinite burn. Revive a Machine monster (e.g: Martial) with "Monster Reborn" and destroy it with "Offerings to the Doomed". Rinse and repeat for constant 300 x 3 = 900 damage in total until your opponent is dead.

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Monster Reborn" is given for free, if you have completed tutorial to save 30 UR!

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contact Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Arcana" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Pot of Acquisitiveness" + "Primal Seed" + "Ravenous" + "Cyber Summon Blaster" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 150 SR and 60 UR!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 90 SR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 690 SR and 150 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. Let me know if you have any questions and have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Fascinating analysis of your future, lucky or unlucky?
deck_description:
On the world geopolitical stage, the Third War was in full force. The United States, known for its global influence, made a serious mistake in underestimating the power of the enemy. After intense conflict, China has emerged as a formidable force, imbued with impressive military might. However, amid this turmoil, an unexpected partnership began to play a significant role in the war: Brazil.

Quietly, Brazil, driven by a sense of justice and solidarity, decided to help China in its battle against the European powers. Help arrived in a variety of ways, from the full of economic resources to the leak of American information to the Chinese on Brazilian soil.

Meanwhile, in the United States, authorities frantically debated where this crucial aid to the enemy came from. Military analysts, with their sharp minds, combed through countless intelligence reports, trying to figure out where these essential resources for China came from. However, the secret of Brazil and China was well guarded, unable to be unraveled.

Amidst this geopolitical strife, a new voice has begun to emerge: that of America's youth. Tired of seeing their country's youth sent to the battlefield, they refused to join the war. A large demonstration was raised among the American population who did not want to have their children killed in the war, a wave of protests across the country.

This insurrection, however, was not enough to change the course of the war. Hostilities continued, and as the months passed, the United States found itself increasingly weak. China, in collaboration with Russia, Brazil and South Africa, formed a powerful and efficient alliance, leaving the Americans with no way out.

In the end, the defeat of the United States was decisive. The military power of the United Nations against the country was overwhelming and, gradually, its lines of defense were being broken. China has emerged as a big winner, sealing its position as a world superpower alongside its powerful allies Brazil, Russia and South Africa.

deck_excerpt: What would Kyoji Yagumo have used at the start of his dueling career?
deck_description:
As an exercise, I'm attempting to derive deck designs for Zexal characters as they would be near the start of the XYZ era (assuming that card release order was mostly like our own). Manga villain Kyoji Yagumo is known for his signature Spider and Underworld cards, but as he's only seen Dueling late in the series, we have no evidence he had all of those cards back when he was participating in tournaments long before Yuma's story started.

As part of the exercise, this deck uses no cards from later than Generation Force. But if anyone has any thoughts about other cards or strategies better suited to the era, or sees something else I missed, feel free to comment. Remember that Synchros are unavailable, as Zexal tries to pretend those don't exist.

deck_excerpt: What would Kite's deck have looked like at the start of his Number-hunting career?
deck_description:
As an exercise, I'm looking at Zexal characters and deriving what their decks might have looked like at the dawn of the XYZ era (Assuming that card release order still mostly resembled our own). With Kite, I actually have a lot to work with, as he was seen using many cards from Photon Shockwave in his introductory duel, along with a few older cards. (Though it's strange that he was using Goddess with the Third Eye as a filler. Even when he got a Fusion monster later that season, fusion substitutes don't work for it.)

As part of the exercise, I'm assuming Kite was one of the first people to get cards from the Photon Shockwave set (even aside from the Photon monsters which would not have been distributed to the public in that world). It's a privilege of working for the people designing and printing the cards in his world. But anything past that wasn't even on the drawing board when he was initially fielded. That said, if there's anything that can be done to refine the deck within these restrictions, feel free to make suggestions.

deck_excerpt: What did Quattro use at the dawn of XYZ - wait, we already know that!
deck_description:
Quattro, born Thomas Arclight, became synonymous with the Gimmick Puppet archetype once he entered the spotlight of Zexal's storyline. Before they were printed, one might have expected him to have tried out Wind-ups... but actually (as Shark was disqualified for seeing) months before the Numbers were unleashed, this young showman was a favorite to win with a Gravekeeper deck.

 

This is based on an actual real-life tournament-winning deck from around 2010-2011, with a few swap-outs for cards that we (and Shark) canonically saw spilled on the floor. It's also lacking an extra deck, as rank 4s seemingly didn't exist yet, and the monster lineup can't manage anything else. (Tremendous Fire is a stand-in for a certain blazing card that doesn't actually exist.) Even so, one can still see how a well-worn deck like this would have taken victory against the newer, uncertain decks in the very first days of XYZ.

Though, perhaps there's something I'm overlooking about how decks were constructed in those days...

deck_excerpt: I asked ChatGPT to make a Synchron Deck.
deck_description:
Prompt: Create a Yu-Gi-Oh Deck that utilizes the "Synchron" archetype to summon multiple Synchro monsters on the first turn.

 

Response: "Creating a Yu-Gi-Oh! deck that focuses on the "Synchron" archetype to summon multiple Synchro monsters on the first turn is an exciting and challenging endeavor. The Synchron archetype is known for its ability to quickly synchro summon powerful monsters by tuning levels and utilizing various Synchron monsters. Here's a sample decklist to help you get started:

 

Main Deck (40 Cards):

  Monsters (22):

  • Junk Synchron x3
  • Quickdraw Synchron x3
  • Doppelwarrior x3
  • Synchron Explorer x2
  • Jet Synchron x3
  • Level Eater x1 (See Point 6 in Adjustments)
  • Unknown Synchron x2
  • Synchron Carrier x2
  • Rush Warrior x1
  • Effect Veiler x2

  Spells (14):

  • Tuning x3
  • Reinforcement of the Army x1
  • One for One x1
  • Foolish Burial x1
  • Upstart Goblin x1
  • Twin Twisters x2
  • Pot of Desires x2
  • Called by the Grave x3 (See Point 5)

  Traps (4):

  • Solemn Strike x2
  • Solemn Judgment x1
  • Solemn Warning x1

 

Extra Deck (15):

  Synchro Monsters (11):

  • Stardust Dragon x1
  • Shooting Quasar Dragon x1
  • Shooting Star Dragon x1
  • T.G. Hyper Librarian x1
  • Accel Synchron x1
  • Formula Synchron x1
  • T.G. Wonder Magician x1
  • Road Warrior x1
  • Jet Warrior x2
  • Black Rose Dragon x1 (See Point 1)

  Xyz Monsters (4):

  • T.G. Recipro Dragonfly x1 (See Point 2)
  • T.G. Hyper Psychic Blaster x1 (See Point 3)
  • Number 39: Utopia x1
  • Number S39: Utopia the Lightning x1

 

Side Deck (15):

  • Cosmic Cyclone x2
  • Red Reboot x2 (See Point 4)
  • Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit x3
  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring x3
  • Dimensional Barrier x2
  • Evenly Matched x3

 

Key Strategies:

  • Tuning and Search: Use cards like "Tuning" and "Reinforcement of the Army" to search for your Synchron monsters, particularly Junk Synchron and Quickdraw Synchron. These are essential pieces for your combos.
  • Level Manipulation: Level Eater and Synchron Carrier help manipulate levels, making it easier to summon Synchro monsters with varying levels.
  • Combo Plays: Combine Quickdraw Synchron with Doppelwarrior and Jet Synchron for explosive combo plays. Quickdraw Synchron's effect lets you summon it easily, and Jet Synchron can be sent from your hand to the graveyard to trigger its effect.
  • Synchro Climbing: Utilize the Synchron monsters and Level Eater to synchro climb into powerful Synchro monsters like Shooting Quasar Dragon and Shooting Star Dragon.
  • Draw Power: Upstart Goblin, Pot of Desires, and the Synchro monsters themselves provide card draw, helping you access key combo pieces.
  • Protection: Solemn Strike, Solemn Judgment, and Solemn Warning are used to protect your combo pieces and prevent your opponent's plays.
  • Side Deck: Customize your side deck to adapt to the current meta and the decks you frequently face. Hand traps like Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit and Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring can help disrupt your opponent's plays.

Remember that piloting a combo-heavy deck like this requires practice to master the sequencing of your plays and adapt to different situations. The extra deck also offers flexibility, so feel free to adjust it based on your preference and the decks you encounter in your local meta."

 

Adjustments:

  • 1: "Jet Black Rose Dragon" does not exist, and was replaced with Black Rose Dragon 
  • 2: "T.G. Recipro Dragonfly"  is not an Xyz monster
  • 3: "T.G. Hyper Psychic Blaster" does not exist, and was replaced with T.G. Blade Blaster 
  • 4: Red Reboot  is banned, and was replaced with Infinite Impermanence 
  • 5: Called by the Grave is Limited, and the 2 copies were replaced with 2 copies of D.D. Crow 
  • 6: Level Eater is banned, and was replaced with Junk Converter

deck_excerpt: Branded Fusion to 1? NO PROBLEM!!! COPIUM
deck_description:
I don't know what the deal with Konami is, but they seem to have a personal vendetta vs. my favourite Yugioh lore hero - Albaz!
 
 Their iconic powerful card, Branded Fusion, has been brought from the original 3, semi-limited to 2, and finally to ONE!!! Why Konami why, must Albaz (and his adoring fanbase, me included) suffer even more??? Branded is not even particularly oppressive (esp. since Expulsion has been banned) and its a general consensus that it is a fun/fair deck to fight against and pilot!
 
Perhaps Konami wants to change the strategy's identity from the over-centralizing resolution Branded Fusion to other forms of play. This harsh limit to the deck's best card forces Branded Despia players to be creative and adapt to the meta, or else they will fall behind with vs. the unstoppable progress of powercreep. 
 
Luckily with all the support Branded Despia has, they're not a one trick pony and have many other plays other than resolving Branded Fusion. There are still many ways to search and recycle Branded Fusion, so that you can be sure that you can use it multiple times over the course of a duel. 

With Tearlaments further weakened, Kashtira not at it's full power level just yet and Spright arguably the strongest deck on ladder, Branded can compete comfortably versus top tier Masterduel meta despite the seemingly critical consistency hit to Branded Fusion. Despite the 50 card decklist, getting to the one copy of Branded Fusion is still very accessible due to the many ways to tutor it out of the deck into hand, and there are multiple ways to recycle the card (that being Retribution, Tragedy and Kitt). 

The second copy of Branded Fusion has been replaced by Keeper of Dragon Magic, whose discard of a card to search any normal fusion spell can help bring a card from hand to GY, triggering Edge Imp Chain's search or enabling Despian Tragedy's GY recovery. It's ability to summon Cartesia or Albaz from the GY, albeit facedown also has some utility, since you are given another piece of material for a fusion summon. 

Other than that one minor change, the deck, strategy and win condition is functionally the same - fusion summon gigantic beatsticks and out-resource your opponent to secure the win! 

If you want a detailed guide with combos on how to pilot Branded Despia, check out my guide for August.
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_description: I was tired of D Barrier so I build this and it works awesome. Just keep in mind that Branded Fusion, Opening und Fusion Deployment locks you into Fusion Monsters.

Vaylantz is a wonderful deck with a lot of weird strategies. This version banks on the fact it can easily go first (setting up Fossil Dyna and Secret Village) whilst maintaining the powerful plays it has going second. I had a lot of fun with Vaylantz and its definitely a great deck to keep around. It will probably never be meta, but is occasionally topping some events, especially in the OCG.

Have fun!
